1
00:00:00,110 --> 00:00:03,800
In this video we are going to learn what are microservices?

2
00:00:04,070 --> 00:00:08,510
Microservices are small, independent and loosely coupled services.

3
00:00:08,510 --> 00:00:15,230
So microservices are small business services that can work together and can be deployed independently

4
00:00:15,230 --> 00:00:16,400
and autonomously.

5
00:00:17,540 --> 00:00:23,030
Each service has a separate code base, which can be managed by a small development team.

6
00:00:23,630 --> 00:00:28,760
A single small team of developers can write and maintain a particular microservices.

7
00:00:29,950 --> 00:00:33,490
Microservices communicates with each other over the network.

8
00:00:33,490 --> 00:00:34,180
Protocols.

9
00:00:34,180 --> 00:00:38,680
Services communicate with each other by using well defined APIs.

10
00:00:38,950 --> 00:00:43,720
Internal implementation details of each service are hidden from the other services.

11
00:00:44,950 --> 00:00:49,870
One of the biggest advantages is that they can be deployed independently.

12
00:00:49,900 --> 00:00:52,630
Microservices can be deployed independently.

13
00:00:52,840 --> 00:00:59,350
A team can update an existing microservice without rebuilding and redeploying the entire application.

14
00:01:00,640 --> 00:01:05,440
Microservices do not need to share the same technology stack libraries or frameworks.

15
00:01:05,470 --> 00:01:11,170
Microservice can work with many different technology stacks, which is technology agnostic.

16
00:01:12,310 --> 00:01:18,820
Microservices has its own database or persistence layer that is not shared with other services.

17
00:01:18,850 --> 00:01:25,420
This is different from the traditional model where a separate data layer handles data persistence.

